Solution: From the inequality between the arithmetic mean and the geometric mean, it follows that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(1+a_{1}\right)\left(1+a_{2}\right) \ldots\left(1+a_{n}\right) & \leq\left(\frac{\left(1+a_{1}\right)+\left(1+a_{2}\right)+\cdots+\left(1+a_{n}\right)}{n}\right)^{n} \\
& =\left(1+\frac{1}{2 n}\right)^{n}=\sqrt{\left(1+\frac{1}{2 n}\right)^{2 n}}
\end{aligned}
$$

On the other hand, for $m \geq 2$ we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(1+\frac{1}{m}\right)^{m} & =\sum_{k=0}^{m}\binom{m}{k} \frac{1}{m^{k}} \\
& <\sum_{k=0}^{m} \frac{1}{k!}=\frac{1}{0!}+\frac{1}{1!}+\sum_{k=2}^{m}\left(\frac{1}{k-1}-\frac{1}{k}\right)=3-\frac{1}{m}
\end{aligned}
$$

Then

$$
\sqrt{\left(1+\frac{1}{2 n}\right)^{2 n}}<\sqrt{3-\frac{1}{2 n}}<\sqrt{3}<2
$$

Remark. The inequality $\left(1+\frac{1}{2 n}\right)^{2 n}<e$, where $e=2.71828 \ldots$ is Euler's number, can also be used. The problem allows for many solutions, including those using induction.

