(Among the possible permutations of $\left(b_{1}, b_{2}, \cdots b_{n}\right)$, there are circular permutations: $\left(b_{2}, b_{3}, \cdots b_{1}\right),\left(b_{3}, b_{4}, \cdots b_{2}\right), \cdots\left(b_{n}, b_{1}, \cdots b_{n-1}\right)$. Each of them allows writing a rearrangement inequality:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n} \geqslant a_{1} b_{2}+a_{2} b_{3}+\cdots a_{n} b_{1} \\
& a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n} \geqslant a_{1} b_{3}+a_{2} b_{4}+\cdots a_{n} b_{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n} \geqslant a_{1} b_{n}+a_{2} b_{1}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n-1}
$$

to which is added: $a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n}=a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n}$.

By adding these $n$ inequalities, we obtain:

$n\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n}\right) \geqslant a_{1}\left(b_{1}+\cdots+b_{n}\right)+a_{2}\left(b_{1}+\cdots+b_{n}\right)+\cdots+a_{n}\left(b_{1}+\cdots+b_{n}\right)$, which is: $n\left(a_{1} b_{1}+a_{2} b_{2}+\cdots a_{n} b_{n}\right) \geqslant\left(a_{1}+\cdots+a_{n}\right)\left(b_{1}+\cdots+b_{n}\right)$.)

